rComments: VIC202 with Komaromi was amazing. She rocks. You'll read important stuff. Take it!

Her reading list for Translation & Comparativity was tough, and did not really cohere for me. I appreciated how she worked with us to try to get a handle on the material - sometimes admitting (to her credit) that it wasn't clear what the theorist was getting at. The mini-quizzes every day were unfortunate; otherwise marking was fair, even generous.

Ms. Komaromi can seem a little distant and uninterested in what you have to say. However, she cares about what she is teaching and that makes her classes enjoyable. The main problem with her course was that she assigned so much reading that we could never go in depth with our analyses of the texts. Great choices of texts, not enough time with them.

She focuses too much on the biographical details of the writers, doing things like running through a list of everything the author wrote.  If these details are necessary, they should be readings.  Her focus on biography and bibliography kept the actual analysis (the reason to go to a literary studies class) to a minimum.
One of the best professors at the school.  Not only does she know her stuff and teach it well, she teahces students how to think and write critically.
Seriously, I think this woman rocks. I went from not being able to pronounce Shalamov to reading "Crime and Punishment" for fun!!! Awesome prof and totally available to chat with.

Prof. Komaromi is awesome! Not only is she fair with her marking, but she gives you appropriate marking methods -- so it's very possible to get a good grade in her class, which is the complete opposite of how so many profs work @ UofT. She has AMAZING taste in literature --- she got me hooked on East Euro. lit.
